# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: layer2-rollups
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Several Layer 2 solutions have been implemented as a result.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network allows near-instant, low-fee payments that settle on the Bitcoin base layer.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] The Liquid Network is a sidechain built on top of Bitcoin which processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] The block size limit, in concert with the proof-of-work difficulty adjustment settings of bitcoin's consensus protocol, constitutes a bottleneck in bitcoin's transaction processing capacity.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] This can result in increasing transaction fees and delayed processing of transactions that cannot be fit into a block.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Various proposals have come forth on how to scale bitcoin, and a contentious debate has resulted.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Technical optimizations may decrease the amount of computing resources required to receive, process and record bitcoin transactions, allowing increased throughput without placing extra demand on the bitcoin network.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] These modifications can be to either the network, in which case a fork is required, or to individual node software (such as Bitcoin Core).
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network (LN) is a protocol that aims to improve bitcoin's scalability and speed without sacrificing trustless operation.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network requires putting a funding transaction on the blockchain to open a payment channel.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Once a channel is opened, connected participants are able to make rapid payments within the channel or may route payments by "hopping" between channels at intermediate nodes for little to no fee.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] In January 2018 Blockstream launched a payment processing system for web retailers called "Lightning Charge", noted that lightning was live on mainnet with 200 nodes operating as of 27 January 2018 and advised it should still be considered "in testing".
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] The Liquid Network is a sidechain that Blockstream developed which is built on top of Bitcoin.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] It processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] On 15 March 2018, Lightning Labs released the beta version of its lnd Lightning Network implementation for bitcoin mainnet, and on 28 March 2018, ACINQ released a mainnet beta of its eclair implementation and desktop application.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] In January 2019 the online retailer Bitrefill announced that it receives more payments in Bitcoin via the lightning network than any other cryptocurrency they accept.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] In June 2021, the Legislative Assembly of El Salvador voted legislation to make Bitcoin legal tender in El Salvador.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] The decision was based on the success of the Bitcoin Beach ecosystem in El Zonte that used a LN based wallet.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] The government will be introducing a wallet utilising the Lightning Network protocol while giving the freedom for citizens to use other Bitcoin Lightning wallets.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] In 2025, El Salvador's bitcoin project was discontinued as a whole.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin has a block time of 10 minutes and a block size of 1 MB.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Various increases to this limit, and proposals to remove it completely, have been proposed over bitcoin's history.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Implementing any of these proposals involves a fork.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Litecoin produces blocks four times faster than Bitcoin which leads to a 4x improvement in throughput.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Dogecoin has even more throughput with a block time of 1 minute.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin Cash has a block size of 32 MB and hence 32x more throughput than Bitcoin.
[src:layer2-rollups/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin SV removed the block size limit altogether.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] As the number of people using Ethereum has grown, the blockchain has reached certain capacity limitations.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] This has driven up the cost of using the network, creating the need for "scaling solutions." There are multiple solutions being researched, tested and implemented that take different approaches to achieve similar goals.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] The main goal of scalability is to increase transaction speed (faster finality) and transaction throughput (higher number of transactions per second) without sacrificing decentralization or security.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] On the layer 1 Ethereum blockchain, high demand leads to slower transactions and nonviable gas prices.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Increasing the network capacity in terms of speed and throughput is fundamental to the meaningful and mass adoption of Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] While speed and throughput are important, it is essential that scaling solutions enabling these goals remain decentralized and secure.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Keeping the barrier to entry low for node operators is critical in preventing a progression towards centralized and insecure computing power.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Conceptually we first categorize scaling as either onchain scaling or offchain scaling.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] You should have a good understanding of all the foundational topics.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Implementing scaling solutions is advanced as the technology is less battle-tested, and continues to be researched and developed.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Onchain scaling requires changes to the Ethereum protocol (layer 1 ).
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] For a long time, sharding the blockchain was expected to scale Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] This was going to involve splitting the blockchain into discrete pieces (shards) to be verified by subsets of validators.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] However, scaling by layer-2 rollups has taken over as the primary scaling technique.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] This is supported by the addition of a new cheaper form of data attached to Ethereum blocks that is specially designed to make rollups cheap for users.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Sharding is the process of splitting a database.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Subsets of validators would be responsible for individual shards rather than keeping track of all of Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Sharding was on the Ethereum roadmap for a long time, and was once intended to be shipped before The Merge to proof-of-stake.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] However, the rapid development of layer 2 rollups and the invention of Danksharding (adding blobs of rollup data to Ethereum blocks that can be very efficiently verified by validators) has led the Ethereum community to favour rollup-centric scaling instead of scaling by sharding.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] This will also help to keep Ethereum's consensus logic simpler.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Offchain solutions are implemented separately from layer 1 Mainnet - they require no changes to the existing Ethereum protocol.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Some solutions, known as "layer 2" solutions, derive their security directly from layer 1 Ethereum consensus, such as optimistic rollups, zero-knowledge rollups or state channels.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Other solutions involve the creation of new chains in various forms that derive their security separately from Mainnet, such as sidechains, validiums, or plasma chains.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] These solutions communicate with Mainnet but derive their security differently to obtain a variety of goals.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] This category of offchain solutions derives its security from Mainnet Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Layer 2 is a collective term for solutions designed to help scale your application by handling transactions off the Ethereum Mainnet (layer 1) while taking advantage of the robust decentralized security model of Mainnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Transaction speed suffers when the network is busy, making the user experience poor for certain types of dapps.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] And as the network gets busier, gas prices increase as transaction senders aim to outbid each other.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] This can make using Ethereum very expensive.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Most layer 2 solutions are centered around a server or cluster of servers, each of which may be referred to as a node, validator, operator, sequencer, block producer, or similar term.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Depending on the implementation, these layer 2 nodes may be run by the individuals, businesses or entities that use them, or by a 3rd party operator, or by a large group of individuals (similar to Mainnet).
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Generally speaking, transactions are submitted to these layer 2 nodes instead of being submitted directly to layer 1 (Mainnet).
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] For some solutions, the layer 2 instance then batches them into groups before anchoring them to layer 1, after which they are secured by layer 1 and cannot be altered.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] The details of how this is done vary significantly between different layer 2 technologies and implementations.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] A specific layer 2 instance may be open and shared by many applications, or may be deployed by one project and dedicated to supporting only their application.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] Rollups perform transaction execution outside layer 1 and then the data is posted to layer 1 where consensus is reached.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] As transaction data is included in layer 1 blocks, this allows rollups to be secured by native Ethereum security.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] State channels utilize multisig contracts to enable participants to transact quickly and freely offchain, then settle finality with Mainnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] This minimizes network congestion, fees, and delays.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] The two types of channels are currently state channels and payment channels.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] A sidechain is an independent EVM-compatible blockchain that runs in parallel to Mainnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] These are compatible with Ethereum via two-way bridges and run under their own chosen rules of consensus and block parameters.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] A plasma chain is a separate blockchain that is anchored to the main Ethereum chain and uses fraud proofs (like optimistic rollups) to arbitrate disputes.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] A Validium chain uses validity proofs like zero-knowledge rollups but data is not stored on the main layer 1 Ethereum chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/developers-scaling] This can lead to 10k transactions per second per Validium chain and multiple chains can be run in parallel.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum was conceived in 2013 by programmer Vitalik Buterin.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Other founders include Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, Anthony Di Iorio, and Joseph Lubin.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In 2014, development work began and was crowdfunded, and the network went live on 30 July 2015.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum allows anyone to deploy decentralized applications onto it, which anyone can then use.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) applications provide financial instruments that do not directly rely on financial intermediaries like brokerages, exchanges, or banks.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] This facilitates borrowing against cryptocurrency holdings or lending them out for interest.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum allows users to create fungible (e.g.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] ERC-20) and non-fungible tokens (NFTs) with a variety of properties, and to create smart contracts that can receive, hold and send those assets in accordance with the contract's immutable code and a transaction's input data.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] On 15 September 2022, Ethereum transitioned its consensus mechanism from proof-of-work (PoW) to proof-of-stake (PoS) in an update known as "The Merge", which cut the blockchain's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum was initially described in late 2013 in a white paper by Vitalik Buterin, a programmer and co-founder of *Bitcoin Magazine*, that described a way to build decentralized applications.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Buterin argued to the Bitcoin Core developers that blockchain technology could benefit from other applications besides money and that it needed a more robust language for application development that could lead to attaching real-world assets, such as stocks and property, to the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In 2013, Buterin briefly worked with eToro CEO Yoni Assia on the Colored Coins project and drafted its white paper outlining additional use cases for blockchain technology.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] However, after failing to gain agreement on how the project should proceed, he proposed the development of a new platform with a more robust scripting language—a Turing-complete programming language—that would eventually become Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum was announced at the North American Bitcoin Conference in Miami, in January 2014.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] During the conference, Gavin Wood, Charles Hoskinson, and Anthony Di Iorio (who financed the project) rented a house in Miami with Buterin at which they could develop a fuller sense of what Ethereum might become.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Di Iorio invited friend Joseph Lubin, who invited reporter Morgen Peck, to bear witness.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Peck subsequently wrote about the experience in *Wired*.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Six months later the founders met again in Zug, Switzerland, where Buterin told the founders that the project would proceed as a non-profit.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Hoskinson left the project at that time and soon after founded IOHK, a blockchain company responsible for Cardano.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum has an unusually long list of founders.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Anthony Di Iorio wrote: "Ethereum was founded by Vitalik Buterin, Myself, Charles Hoskinson, Mihai Alisie & Amir Chetrit (the initial 5) in December 2013.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Joseph Lubin, Gavin Wood, & Jeffrey Wilcke were added in early 2014 as founders." Buterin chose the name Ethereum after browsing a list of elements from science fiction on Wikipedia.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Formal development of the software underlying Ethereum began in early 2014 through a Swiss company, Ethereum Switzerland GmbH (*EthSuisse*).The idea of putting executable smart contracts in the blockchain needed to be specified before it could be implemented in software.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] This work was done by Gavin Wood, then the chief technology officer, in the Ethereum Yellow Paper that specified the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Subsequently, a Swiss non-profit foundation, the **Ethereum Foundation** (*Stiftung Ethereum*), was founded.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Development was funded by an online public crowd sale from July to August 2014, in which participants bought the Ethereum value token (ether) with another digital currency, bitcoin.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] While there was early praise for the technical innovations of Ethereum, questions were also raised about its security and scalability.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The intended purpose of the three distinct implementations would be so that if one of them had a bug, the other two could be used as a comparison.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Several codenamed prototypes of Ethereum were developed over 18 months in 2014 and 2015 by the Ethereum Foundation as part of their proof-of-concept series.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] "Olympic" was the last prototype and public beta pre-release.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The Olympic network gave users a bug bounty of 25,000 ether for stress-testing the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] On 30 July 2015, "Frontier" marked the official launch of the Ethereum platform, and Ethereum created its "genesis block".
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The genesis block contained 8,893 transactions allocating various amounts of ether to different addresses, and a block reward of 5 ETH.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Since the initial launch, Ethereum has undergone a number of planned protocol upgrades, which are important changes affecting the underlying functionality and/or incentive structures of the platform.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Protocol upgrades are accomplished by means of a hard fork.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In 2016, a decentralized autonomous organization called The DAO—a set of smart contracts developed on the platform—raised a record US$150 million in a crowd sale to fund the project.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Emin Gün Sirer, Vlad Zamfir and Dino Mark had written a paper called *A Call for a Temporary Moratorium on The DAO* in which they described in which way the DAO might be vunerable to attacks.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The DAO was exploited in June 2016 when US$50 million of DAO tokens were stolen by an unknown hacker.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The event sparked a debate in the crypto-community about whether Ethereum should perform a contentious "hard fork" to reappropriate the affected funds.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The fork resulted in the network splitting into two blockchains: Ethereum with the theft reversed, and Ethereum Classic which continued on the original chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In March 2017, various blockchain startups, research groups, and *Fortune* 500 companies announced the creation of the Enterprise Ethereum Alliance (EEA) with 30 founding members.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] By May 2017, the nonprofit organization had 116 enterprise members, including ConsenSys, CME Group, Cornell University's research group, Toyota Research Institute, Samsung SDS, Microsoft, Intel, J.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Morgan, Cooley LLP, Merck KGaA, DTCC, Deloitte, Accenture, Banco Santander, BNY Mellon, ING, and National Bank of Canada.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] By July 2017, there were over 150 members in the alliance, including MasterCard, Cisco Systems, Sberbank, and Scotiabank.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In 2024, Paul Brody, EEA board member for EY, was announced as the new chairperson, and Karen Scarbrough, board member for Microsoft, as the new executive director.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Vanessa Grellet from Arche Capital also joined as a new board member.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In 2017, *CryptoKitties*, the blockchain game and decentralized application (dApp) featuring digital cat artwork as NFTs, was launched on the Ethereum network.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In cultivating popularity with users and collectors, it gained notable mainstream media attention providing significant exposure to Ethereum in the process.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] It was considered the most popular smart contract in use on the network but it also highlighted concerns over Ethereum's scalability due to the game's substantial consumption of network capacity at the time.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In January 2018, a community-driven paper (an EIP, "Ethereum Improvement Proposal") under the leadership of civic hacker and lead author William Entriken was published, called *ERC-721: Non-Fungible Token Standard.* It introduced ERC-721, the first official NFT standard on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] This standardization allowed Ethereum to become central to a multi-billion dollar digital collectibles market.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] By January 2018, ether was the second-largest cryptocurrency in terms of market capitalization, behind bitcoin.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] As of 2021, it maintained that relative position.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In 2019, Ethereum Foundation employee Virgil Griffith was arrested by the US government for presenting at a blockchain conference in North Korea.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] He would later plead guilty to one count of conspiring to violate the International Emergency Economic Powers Act in 2021.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In March 2021, Visa Inc. announced that it began settling stablecoin transactions using Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In April 2021, JP Morgan Chase, UBS, and MasterCard announced that they were investing US$65 million into ConsenSys, a software development firm that builds Ethereum-related infrastructure.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] There were two network upgrades in 2021.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The first was "Berlin", implemented on 14 April 2021.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The second was "London", which took effect on 5 August.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The London upgrade included Ethereum Improvement Proposal ("EIP") 1559, a mechanism for reducing transaction fee volatility.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The mechanism causes a portion of the ether paid in transaction fees for each block to be destroyed rather than given to the block proposer, reducing the inflation rate of ether and potentially resulting in periods of deflation.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] On 27 August 2021, the blockchain experienced a brief fork that was the result of clients running different incompatible software versions.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] "The Merge" (formerly called Ethereum 2.0) was a set of three updates (Bellatrix, Paris, and Shapella) that transitioned Ethereum's consensus protocol from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Bellatrix updated the proof-of-stake Beacon chain and introduced economic slashing.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Paris was the event at block 15537393 on 15 September 2022 that merged Ethereum to the Beacon chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Shapella (Shanghai-Capella) was the update that allowed for staking withdrawals.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The switch from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake has cut Ethereum's energy usage by over 99%.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] However, the effect this has on global energy consumption and climate change may be limited since the computers previously used for mining ether may be used to mine other cryptocurrencies that are energy-intensive.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] On 13 March 2024, "Dencun" or also "Deneb-Cancun" set of upgrades went live.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] These included EIP-4844 (Proto-Danksharding) which introduced "blobs" that can be used for general-purpose data-availability.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Because "Blob" data is stored only temporarily, it is much cheaper than using normal call data for storage.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] This allows for Ethereum Layer 2 (L2) networks to greatly reduce the cost of posting compressed transaction data to the Layer 1 (L1).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The Prague-Electra ("Pectra") update was launched on 7 May 2025.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The Fulu-Osaka update went live on 3 December 2025.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] This update introduced several protocol improvements.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum is a peer-to-peer network that maintains a database containing the storage values of all Ethereum accounts and processes state-altering transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Approximately every 12 seconds, a batch of new transactions, known as a "block", is processed by the network.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Each block contains a cryptographic hash identifying the series of blocks that must precede it if the block is to be considered valid.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] This series of blocks is known as the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Each "node" (network participant) connects with a relatively small subset of the network to offer blocks and unvalidated transactions (i.e. transactions not yet in the blockchain) to its peers for download, and it downloads any from its peers that it doesn't already have.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Each node usually has a unique set of peers, so that offering an item to its peers results in the propagation of that item throughout the entire network within seconds.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] A node's collection of unvalidated transactions is known as its "mempool".
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] A node may choose to create a copy of the state for itself.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] It does this by starting with the genesis state and executing every transaction in the blockchain, in the proper order of blocks and in the order they are listed within each block.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may "stake" (deposit) 32 or more ETH to register a "validator".
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] At the end of each "epoch" (32 block slots, each slot lasting 12 seconds), each validator is pseudorandomly assigned to one of the slots of the epoch after the next, either as the block proposer or as an attester.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] During a slot, the block proposer uses their mempool to create a block that is intended to become the new "head" (latest block) of the blockchain, and the attesters attest to which block is at the head of the chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] If a validator makes self-contradicting proposals or attestations, or if it is inactive, it loses a portion of its stake.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Any Ethereum account may send ETH to a validator at any time to increase its stake.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] A validator's attestation is given a weight equal to its stake or 2,048, whichever is less.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] According to the Ethereum protocol, the blockchain with the highest accumulated weight of attestations at any given time is to be regarded as the canonical chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Validators are rewarded for making valid proposals and attestations.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] A validator's rewards are paid via transactions within the same chain that contains their proposal or attestation, and therefore would have little or no market value unless that chain becomes the canonical chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] This incentivizes validators to support the chain that they think other validators view as the canonical chain, which results in a high degree of consensus.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ether (ETH) is the cryptocurrency generated in accordance with the Ethereum protocol as a reward to validators in a proof-of-stake system for adding blocks to the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ether is represented in the state as an unsigned integer associated with each account, this being the account's ETH balance denominated in wei (1018 wei = 1 ether).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] At the end of each epoch, new ETH is generated by the addition of protocol-specified amounts to the balances of all validators that made valid block proposals or attestations in the epoch before the last (i.e. the epoch being finalized).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Additionally, ether is the only currency accepted by the protocol as payment for the transaction fee.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The transaction fee is composed of two parts: the base fee and the tip.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The base fee is "burned" (deleted from existence) and the tip goes to the block proposer.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The validator reward together with the tips provide the incentive to validators to keep the blockchain growing (i.e. to keep processing new transactions).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Therefore, ETH is fundamental to the operation of the network.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ether may be "sent" from one account to another via a transaction, the execution of which simply entails subtracting the *amount to be sent* from the sender's balance and adding the same amount to the recipient's balance.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ether is often erroneously referred to as "Ethereum".
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The uppercase Greek letter Xi, Ξ, is sometimes used as a currency symbol for ether.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] There are two types of accounts on Ethereum: user accounts (also known as externally-owned accounts), and contract accounts.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Both types have an ETH balance, may transfer ETH to any account, may execute the code of another contract, or create a new contract, and are identified on the blockchain and in the state by an account address.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Contracts are the only type of account that has associated bytecode and storage (to store contract-specific state).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The code of a contract is evaluated when a transaction is sent to it.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The code of the contract may read user-specified data from the transaction, and may have a return value.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum account addresses are composed of the prefix "`0x`" (a common identifier for hexadecimal) concatenated with the rightmost 20 bytes of the Keccak-256 hash of the ECDSA public key (the curve used is the so-called *secp256k1*).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In hexadecimal, two digits represent a byte, and so addresses contain 40 hexadecimal digits after the "`0x`", e.g.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Contract addresses are in the same format, however, they are determined by sender and creation transaction nonce.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM) is the runtime environment for transaction execution in Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The EVM is a stack based virtual machine with an instruction set specifically designed for Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The instruction set includes, among other things, stack operations, memory operations, and operations to inspect the current execution context, such as remaining gas, information about the current block, and the current transaction.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The EVM is designed to be deterministic on a wide variety of hardware and operating systems, so that given a pre-transaction state and a transaction, each node produces the same post-transaction state, thereby enabling network consensus.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The formal definition of the EVM is specified in the Ethereum Yellow Paper.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] EVMs have been implemented in C++, C#, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Python, Ruby, Rust, Elixir, Erlang, and soon WebAssembly.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Gas is a unit of account within the EVM used in the calculation of the transaction fee, which is the amount of ETH a transaction's sender must pay to the network to have the transaction included in the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Each type of operation which may be performed by the EVM is hardcoded with a certain gas cost, which is intended to be roughly proportional to the monetary value of the resources (e.g. computation and storage) a node must expend or dedicate to perform that operation.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] When a sender is creating a transaction, the sender must specify a *gas limit* and *gas price*.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The *gas limit* is the maximum amount of gas the sender is willing to use in the transaction, and the *gas price* is the amount of ETH the sender wishes to pay to the network per unit of gas used.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] A transaction may only be included in the blockchain at a block slot that has a *base gas price* less than or equal to the transaction's *gas price*.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The portion of the *gas price* that is in excess of the *base gas price* is known as the tip and goes to the block proposer; the higher the tip, the more incentive a block proposer has to include the transaction in their block, and thus the quicker the transaction will be included in the blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The sender buys the full amount of gas (i.e. their ETH balance is debited *gas limit* × *gas price* and their gas balance is set to *gas limit*) up-front, at the start of the execution of the transaction, and is refunded at the end for any unused gas.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] If at any point the transaction does not have enough gas to perform the next operation, the transaction is reverted but the sender is still only refunded for the unused gas.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In user interfaces, gas prices are typically denominated in gigawei (Gwei), a subunit of ETH equal to 10−9 ETH.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The EVM's instruction set is Turing-complete.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum's smart contracts are written in high-level programming languages and then compiled down to EVM bytecode, which is then deployed to the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] They can be written in Solidity (a language library with similarities to C and JavaScript), as well as others.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Source code and compiler information are usually published on blockchain explorer websites soon after the launch of the contract so that users can see the code and verify that it compiles to the bytecode that is on-chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] One issue related to using smart contracts on a public blockchain is that bugs, including security holes, are visible to all but cannot be fixed quickly.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] One example of this is the 2016 attack on The DAO, which could not be quickly stopped or reversed.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The ERC-20 (Ethereum Request-for-Comments #20) Token Standard allows for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The standard, proposed by Fabian Vogelsteller in November 2015, implements an API for tokens within smart contracts.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The standard provides functions that include the transfer of tokens from one account to another, getting the current token balance of an account, and getting the total supply of the token available on the network.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Smart contracts that correctly implement ERC-20 processes are called ERC-20 Token Contracts, and they keep track of created tokens on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Numerous cryptocurrencies have launched as ERC-20 tokens and have been distributed through initial coin offerings.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum also allows for the creation of unique and indivisible tokens, called non-fungible tokens (NFTs).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Since tokens of this type are unique, they have been used to represent such things as collectibles, digital art, sports memorabilia, virtual real estate, and items within games.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] ERC-721 is the first official NFT standard for Ethereum and was followed up by ERC-1155 which introduced semi-fungibility; both are widely used, though some fully fungible tokens using ERC-20 have been used for NFTs such as *CryptoPunks*.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The first NFT project, Etheria, a 3D map of tradable and customizable hexagonal tiles, was deployed to the network in October 2015 and demonstrated live at DEVCON1 in November of that year.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In 2021, Christie's sold a digital image with an NFT by Beeple for US$69.3 million, making him the third-most-valuable living artist in terms of auction prices at the time, although observers have noted that both the buyer and seller had a vested interest in driving demand for the artist's work.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Decentralized finance (DeFi) offers financial instruments in a decentralized architecture, outside of companies' and governments' control, such as money market funds which let users earn interest.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] DeFi applications are typically accessed through a Web3-enabled browser extension or application, such as MetaMask, which allows users to directly interact with the Ethereum blockchain through a website.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Many of these DApps can connect and work together to create complex financial services.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Examples of DeFi platforms include MakerDAO.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Uniswap, a decentralized exchange for tokens on Ethereum grew from US$20 million in liquidity to US$2.9 billion in 2020.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] As of October 2020, over US$11 billion was invested in various DeFi protocols.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Additionally, through a process called "wrapping", certain DeFi protocols allow synthetic versions of various assets (such as bitcoin, gold, and oil) to be tradeable on Ethereum and also compatible with all of Ethereum's major wallets and applications.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Aave is a protocol for microlending using Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum-based software and networks, independent from the public Ethereum chain, have been tested by enterprise software companies.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Interested parties have included Microsoft, IBM, JPMorgan Chase, Deloitte, R3, and Innovate UK (cross-border payments prototype).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Barclays, UBS, Credit Suisse, Amazon, Visa, and other companies have also experimented with Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] As of December 2025, the maximum theoretical throughput for Ethereum L1 is 238 TPS (given its current 60M gas limit, 12s blocks, and 21k gas cost for ETH transfers).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Due to large smart contract and batch transaction using more gas in each block, the average transaction throughput is much less.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] As of January 2016, the Ethereum averaged about 25 transactions per second; this did not change after the move to proof-of-stake.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In comparison, the Visa payment platform processes 45,000 payments per second.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] This has led some to question the scalability of Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Ethereum's blockchain uses a Merkle–Patricia Tree to store account state in each block.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The trie allows for storage savings, set membership proofs (called "Merkle proofs"), and light client synchronization.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The network has faced congestion problems, such as in 2017 in relation to *CryptoKitties*.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Layer 2 (L2) is one of the approaches that the Ethereum ecosystem has developed in order to scale up and handle more transactions with lower transaction fees.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] A Layer 2 chain is a separate blockchain that extends Ethereum (Layer 1) and inherits the security guarantees of Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] There are different types of L2 chains, including optimistic rollups and zero-knowledge rollups (zk rollups).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Depending on their individual technical details, some L2 chains are capable of processing thousands of transactions per second.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The legal status of ether (ETH), Ethereum's native token, remains subject to uncertainty and varies substantially from one jurisdiction to another.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In the United States, regulatory authorities have increasingly signaled that ether should be treated as a commodity under the jurisdiction of the Commodity Futures Trading Commission (CFTC).
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] The CFTC has repeatedly asserted its regulatory authority over Ethereum, with former CFTC Chairman Heath Tarbert stating in 2019 that "ETH is a commodity" and subsequent leadership maintaining this position.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] From a private law perspective, many jurisdictions have recognized ether as a form of intangible personal property that can be owned, transferred, and used as collateral, similar to other forms of personal property.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] In the United States specifically, the 2022 Amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property that includes digital assets like ether.
[src:layer2-rollups/ethereum] Under UCC Article 12, ETH is classified as a CER, which provides a comprehensive framework for its commercial circulation.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups are layer 2 (L2) protocols designed to extend the throughput of Ethereum's base layer.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] They reduce computation on the main Ethereum chain by processing transactions offchain, offering significant improvements in processing speeds.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Unlike other scaling solutions, such as sidechains, optimistic rollups derive security from Mainnet by publishing transaction results onchain, or plasma chains, which also verify transactions on Ethereum with fraud proofs, but store transaction data elsewhere.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] As computation is the slow, expensive part of using Ethereum, optimistic rollups can offer up to 10-100x improvements in scalability.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups also write transactions to Ethereum as `calldata` or in blobs, reducing gas costs for users.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] You should have read and understood our pages on Ethereum scaling and layer 2.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] An optimistic rollup is an approach to scaling Ethereum that involves moving computation and state storage offchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups execute transactions outside of Ethereum, but post transaction data to Mainnet as `calldata` or in blobs.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollup operators bundle multiple offchain transactions together in large batches before submitting to Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This approach enables spreading fixed costs across multiple transactions in each batch, reducing fees for end-users.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups also use compression techniques to reduce the amount of data posted on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups are considered “optimistic” because they assume offchain transactions are valid and don't publish proofs of validity for transaction batches posted onchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This separates optimistic rollups from zero-knowledge rollups that publish cryptographic for offchain transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups instead rely on a fraud-proving scheme to detect cases where transactions are not calculated correctly.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] After a rollup batch is submitted on Ethereum, there's a time window (called a challenge period) during which anyone can challenge the results of a rollup transaction by computing a .
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If the fraud proof succeeds, the rollup protocol re-executes the transaction(s) and updates the rollup's state accordingly.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The other effect of a successful fraud proof is that the sequencer responsible for including the incorrectly executed transaction in a block receives a penalty.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If the rollup batch remains unchallenged (i.e., all transactions are correctly executed) after the challenge period elapses, it is deemed valid and accepted on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Others can continue to build on an unconfirmed rollup block, but with a caveat: transaction results will be reversed if based on an incorrectly executed transaction published previously.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups are offchain scaling solutions built to operate on top of Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Each optimistic rollup is managed by a set of smart contracts deployed on the Ethereum network.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups process transactions off the main Ethereum chain, but post offchain transactions (in batches) to an onchain rollup contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] As optimistic rollups are designed to run programs either written or compiled for the EVM, the offchain VM incorporates many EVM design specs.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Additionally, fraud proofs computed onchain allow the Ethereum network to enforce the validity of state changes computed in the offchain VM.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups are described as 'hybrid scaling solutions' because, while they exist as separate protocols, their security properties are derived from Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Among other things, Ethereum guarantees the correctness of a rollup’s offchain computation and the availability of data behind the computation.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This makes optimistic rollups more secure than pure offchain scaling protocols (e.g., sidechains) that do not rely on Ethereum for security.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] As mentioned, optimistic rollups post transaction data to Ethereum as `calldata` or blobs.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Since the rollup chain's execution is based on submitted transactions, anyone can use this information—anchored on Ethereum’s base layer—to execute the rollup’s state and verify the correctness of state transitions.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Data availability is critical because without access to state data, challengers cannot construct fraud proofs to dispute invalid rollup operations.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] With Ethereum providing data availability, the risk of rollup operators getting away with malicious acts (e.g., submitting invalid blocks) is reduced.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups also rely on Ethereum for censorship resistance.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] In an optimistic rollup a centralized entity (the operator) is responsible for processing transactions and submitting rollup blocks to Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups solve this problem by forcing operators to publish data associated with state updates on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Another role Ethereum plays in the context of optimistic rollups is that of a settlement layer.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] A settlement layer anchors the entire blockchain ecosystem, establishes security, and provides objective finality if a dispute occurs on another chain (optimistic rollups in this case) that requires arbitration.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Ethereum Mainnet provides a hub for optimistic rollups to verify fraud proofs and resolve disputes.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Moreover, transactions conducted on the rollup are only final *after* the rollup block is accepted on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Once a rollup transaction is committed to Ethereum’s base layer, it cannot be rolled back (except in the highly unlikely case of a chain reorganization).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Users submit transactions to “operators”, which are nodes responsible for processing transactions on the optimistic rollup.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Also known as a “validator” or “aggregator”, the operator aggregates transactions, compresses the underlying data, and publishes the block on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Although anyone can become a validator, optimistic rollup validators must provide a bond before producing blocks, much like a proof-of-stake system.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This bond can be slashed if the validator posts an invalid block or builds on an old-but-invalid block (even if their block is valid).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This way optimistic rollups utilize cryptoeconomic incentives to ensure validators act honestly.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Other validators on the optimistic rollup chain are expected to execute the submitted transactions using their copy of the rollup’s state.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If a validator’s final state is different from the operator’s proposed state, they can start a challenge and compute a fraud proof.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Some optimistic rollups may forgo a permissionless validator system and use a single “sequencer” to execute the chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Like a validator, the sequencer processes transactions, produces rollup blocks, and submits rollup transactions to the L1 chain (Ethereum).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The sequencer is different from a regular rollup operator because they have greater control over the ordering of transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Also, the sequencer has priority access to the rollup chain and is the only entity authorized to submit transactions to the onchain contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Transactions from non-sequencer nodes or regular users are simply queued up in a separate inbox until the sequencer includes them in a new batch.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] As mentioned, the operator of an optimistic rollup bundles offchain transactions into a batch and sends it to Ethereum for notarization.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This process involves compressing transaction-related data and publishing it on Ethereum as `calldata` or in blobs.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] `calldata` is a non-modifiable, non-persistent area in a smart contract that behaves mostly like memory.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] While `calldata` persists onchain as part of the blockchain's history logs (opens in a new tab), it is not stored as a part of Ethereum's state.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Because `calldata` does not touch any part of Ethereum's state, it is cheaper than state for storing data onchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The `calldata` keyword is also used in Solidity to pass arguments to a smart contract function at execution time.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] `calldata` identifies the function being called during a transaction and holds inputs to the function in the form of an arbitrary sequence of bytes.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] In the context of optimistic rollups, `calldata` is used to send compressed transaction data to the onchain contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The rollup operator adds a new batch by calling the required function in the rollup contract and passing the compressed data as function arguments.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Using `calldata` reduces user fees since most costs that rollups incur come from storing data onchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Here is an example (opens in a new tab) of a rollup batch submission to show how this concept works.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The sequencer invoked the `appendSequencerBatch()` method and passed the compressed transaction data as inputs using `calldata`.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Some rollups now use blobs to post batches of transactions to Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Blobs are non-modifiable and non-persistent (just like `calldata`) but are pruned from history after ~18 days.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] For more information on blobs, see Danksharding.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] At any point in time, the optimistic rollup’s state (accounts, balances, contract code, etc.) is organized as a Merkle tree called a “state tree”.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The root of this Merkle tree (state root), which references the rollup’s latest state, is hashed and stored in the rollup contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Every state transition on the chain produces a new rollup state, which an operator commits to by computing a new state root.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The operator is required to submit both old state roots and new state roots when posting batches.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If the old state root matches the existing state root in the onchain contract, the latter is discarded and replaced with the new state root.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The rollup operator is also required to commit a Merkle root for the transaction batch itself.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This allows anyone to prove the inclusion of a transaction in the batch (on L1) by presenting a Merkle proof.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] State commitments, especially state roots, are necessary for proving the correctness of state changes in an optimistic rollup.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The rollup contract accepts new state roots from operators immediately after they are posted, but can later delete invalid state roots to restore the rollup to its correct state.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] As explained, optimistic rollups allow anyone to publish blocks without providing proofs of validity.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] However, to ensure the chain remains safe, optimistic rollups specify a time window during which anyone can dispute a state transition.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Hence, rollup blocks are called “assertions” since anyone can dispute their validity.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If someone disputes an assertion, then the rollup protocol will initiate the fraud proof computation.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Every type of fraud proof is interactive—someone must post an assertion before another person can challenge it.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The difference lies in how many rounds of interaction are required to compute the fraud proof.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Single-round interactive proving schemes replay disputed transactions on L1 to detect invalid assertions.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The rollup protocol emulates the re-execution of the disputed transaction on L1 (Ethereum) using a verifier contract, with the computed state root determining who wins the challenge.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If the challenger's claim about the rollup’s correct state is correct, the operator is penalized by having their bond slashed.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] However, re-executing transactions on L1 to detect fraud requires publishing state commitments for individual transactions and increases the data rollups must publish onchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Replaying transactions also incurs significant gas costs.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] For these reasons, optimistic rollups are switching to multi-round interactive proving, which achieves the same objective (i.e., detecting invalid rollup operations) with more efficiency.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Multi-round interactive proving involves a back-and-forth protocol between the asserter and challenger overseen by an L1 verifier contract, which ultimately decides the lying party.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] After an L2 node challenges an assertion, the asserter is required to divide the disputed assertion into two equal halves.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Each individual assertion in this case will contain as many steps of computation as the other.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The challenger will then choose what assertion it wants to challenge.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The dividing process (called a “bisection protocol”) continues until both parties are disputing an assertion about a *single* step of execution.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] At this point, the L1 contract will resolve the dispute by evaluating the instruction (and its result) to catch the fraudulent party.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The asserter is required to provide a “one-step proof” verifying the validity of the disputed single-step computation.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If the asserter fails to provide the one-step proof, or the L1 verifier deems the proof invalid, they lose the challenge.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Bisection protocols reduce the amount of data posted onchain (no need to publish state commits for every transaction).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Also, optimistic rollup transactions are not constrained by Ethereum's gas limit.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Conversely, optimistic rollups re-executing transactions must make sure an L2 transaction has a lower gas limit to emulate its execution within a single Ethereum transaction.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Part of the malicious asserter's bond is awarded to the challenger, while the other part is burned.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The burning prevents collusion among validators; if two validators collude to initiate bogus challenges, they will still forfeit a considerable chunk of the entire stake.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Multi-round interactive proving requires both parties (the asserter and the challenger) to make moves within the specified time window.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Failure to act before the deadline expires causes the defaulting party to forfeit the challenge.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Fraud proofs are important because they facilitate *trustless finality* in optimistic rollups.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Trustless finality is a quality of optimistic rollups that guarantees that a transaction—so long as it’s valid—will eventually be confirmed.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Malicious nodes can try to delay the confirmation of a valid rollup block by starting false challenges.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] However, fraud proofs will eventually prove the rollup block’s validity and cause it to be confirmed.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This also relates to another security property of optimistic rollups: the validity of the chain relies on the existence of *one* honest node.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The honest node can advance the chain correctly by either posting valid assertions or disputing invalid assertions.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Whatever the case, malicious nodes who enter into disputes with the honest node will lose their stakes during the fraud proving process.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups are designed for interoperability with Ethereum Mainnet and allow users to pass messages and arbitrary data between L1 and L2.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] They are also compatible with the EVM, so you can port existing dapps to optimistic rollups or create new dapps using Ethereum development tools.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] To use an optimistic rollup, users deposit ETH, ERC-20 tokens, and other accepted assets in the rollup’s bridge contract on L1.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The bridge contract will relay the transaction to L2, where an equivalent amount of assets is minted and sent to the user’s chosen address on the optimistic rollup.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] User-generated transactions (like an L1 > L2 deposit) are usually queued until the sequencer re-submits them to the rollup contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] However, to preserve censorship resistance, optimistic rollups allow users to submit a transaction directly to the onchain rollup contract if it has been delayed past the maximum time allowed.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Some optimistic rollups adopt a more straightforward approach to prevent sequencers from censoring users.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Here, a block is defined by all transactions submitted to the L1 contract since the previous block (e.g., deposits) in addition to the transactions processed on the rollup chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If a sequencer ignores an L1 transaction, it will publish the (provably) wrong state root; therefore, sequencers cannot delay user-generated messages once posted on L1.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Withdrawing from an optimistic rollup to Ethereum is more difficult owing to the fraud proving scheme.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If a user initiates an L2 > L1 transaction to withdraw funds escrowed on L1, they must wait until the challenge period—lasting roughly seven days—elapses.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Nevertheless, the withdrawal process itself is fairly straightforward.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] After the withdrawal request is initiated on the L2 rollup, the transaction is included in the next batch, while the user’s assets on the rollup are burned.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Once the batch is published on Ethereum, the user can compute a Merkle proof verifying the inclusion of their exit transaction in the block.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Then it is a matter of waiting through the delay period to finalize the transaction on L1 and withdraw funds to Mainnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] To avoid waiting a week before withdrawing funds to Ethereum, optimistic rollup users can employ a **liquidity provider** (LP).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] A liquidity provider assumes ownership of a pending L2 withdrawal and pays the user on L1 (in exchange for a fee).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Liquidity providers can check the validity of the user’s withdrawal request (by executing the chain themselves) before releasing funds.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This way they have assurances that the transaction will be confirmed eventually (i.e., trustless finality).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] For developers, the advantage of optimistic rollups is their compatibility—or, better still, equivalence—with the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] EVM-compatible rollups comply with specifications in the Ethereum Yellow Paper (opens in a new tab) and support the EVM at the bytecode level.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Developers can migrate existing smart contracts on Ethereum to optimistic rollup chains without having to modify codebases extensively.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This can save development teams time when deploying Ethereum smart contracts on L2.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Developers and project teams using optimistic rollups can take advantage of Ethereum's infrastructure.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This includes programming languages, code libraries, testing tools, client software, deployment infrastructure, and so on.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Using existing tooling is important because these tools have been extensively audited, debugged, and improved over the years.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] It also removes the need for Ethereum developers to learn how to build with an entirely new development stack.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Users (externally owned accounts) interact with L2 contracts by submitting a transaction to the rollup contract or having a sequencer or validator do it for them.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups also allow contract accounts on Ethereum to interact with L2 contracts using bridging contracts to relay messages and pass data between L1 and L2.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This means you can program an L1 contract on Ethereum Mainnet to invoke functions belonging to contracts on an L2 optimistic rollup.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Cross-chain contract calls happen asynchronously—meaning the call is initiated first, then executed at a later time.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This is different from calls between the two contracts on Ethereum, where the call produces results immediately.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] An example of a cross-chain contract call is the token deposit described earlier.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] A contract on L1 escrows the user's tokens and sends a message to a paired L2 contract to mint an equal amount of tokens on the rollup.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] As cross-chain message calls result in contract execution, the sender is usually required to cover gas costs for computation.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] It is advisable to set a high gas limit to prevent the transaction from failing on the target chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The token bridging scenario is a good example; if the L1 side of the transaction (depositing the tokens) works, but the L2 side (minting new tokens) fails due to low gas, the deposit becomes irrecoverable.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Finally, we should note that L2 > L1 message calls between contracts need to account for delays (L1 > L2 calls are typically executed after some minutes).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This is because messages sent to Mainnet from the optimistic rollup cannot be executed until the challenge window expires.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups use a gas fee scheme, much like Ethereum, to denote how much users pay per transaction.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] **Blob gas used**: Blob-carrying transactions employ a dynamic fee mechanism similar to the one introduced by EIP-1559 (opens in a new tab).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The gas fee for type-3 transactions takes into account the base fee for blobs, which is determined by the network based on blob-space demand and the blob-space usage of the transaction being sent.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] **L2 operator fees**: This is the amount paid to the rollup nodes as compensation for computational costs incurred in processing transactions, much like gas fees on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Rollup nodes charge lower transaction fees since L2s have higher processing capacities and aren't faced with the network congestions that force validators on Ethereum to prioritize transactions with higher fees.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups apply several mechanisms to reducing fees for users, including batching transactions and compressing `calldata` to reduce data publication costs.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] You can check the L2 fee tracker (opens in a new tab) for a real-time overview of how much it costs to use Ethereum-based optimistic rollups.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] As explained, optimistic rollups publish compressed transaction data on Ethereum to guarantee data availability.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The ability to compress data published onchain is crucial to scaling throughput on Ethereum with optimistic rollups.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The main Ethereum chain places limits on how much data blocks can hold, denominated in gas units (the average block size is 15 million gas).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] While this restricts how much gas each transaction can use, it also means we can increase transactions processed per block by reducing transaction-related data—directly improving scalability.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Optimistic rollups use several techniques to achieve transaction data compression and improve TPS rates.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If a basic rollup transaction uses 12 bytes, then the average Ethereum block can process **78,125 rollup transactions** (937,500/12) or **39 rollup batches** (if each batch holds an average of 2,000 transactions).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] If a new block is produced on Ethereum every 15 seconds, then the rollup's processing speeds would amount to roughly **5,208 transactions per second**.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This is done by dividing the number of basic rollup transactions an Ethereum block can hold (**78,125**) by the average block time (**15 seconds**).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] This is a fairly optimistic estimate, given that optimistic rollup transactions cannot possibly comprise an entire block on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] However, it can give a rough idea of how much scalability gains that optimistic rollups can afford Ethereum users (current implementations offer up to 2,000 TPS).
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] The introduction of data sharding on Ethereum is expected to improve scalability in optimistic rollups.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Because rollup transactions must share blockspace with other non-rollup transactions, their processing capacity is limited by data throughput on the main Ethereum chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/optimistic-rollups] Danksharding will increase the space available to L2 chains to publish data per block, using cheaper, impermanent "blob" storage instead of expensive, permanent `CALLDATA`.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Zero-knowledge rollups (ZK-rollups) are layer 2 scaling solutions that increase throughput on Ethereum Mainnet by moving computation and state-storage offchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups can process thousands of transactions in a batch and then only post some minimal summary data to Mainnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This summary data defines the changes that should be made to the Ethereum state and some cryptographic proof that those changes are correct.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] You should have read and understood our page on Ethereum scaling and layer 2.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The ZK-rollup's state is maintained by a smart contract deployed on the Ethereum network.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] To update this state, ZK-rollup nodes must submit a validity proof for verification.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] As mentioned, the validity proof is a cryptographic assurance that the state-change proposed by the rollup is really the result of executing the given batch of transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This means that ZK-rollups only need to provide validity proofs to finalize transactions on Ethereum instead of posting all transaction data onchain like optimistic rollups.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] There are no delays when moving funds from a ZK-rollup to Ethereum because exit transactions are executed once the ZK-rollup contract verifies the validity proof.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Conversely, withdrawing funds from optimistic rollups is subject to a delay to allow anyone to challenge the exit transaction with a .
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups write transactions to Ethereum as `calldata`.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] `calldata` is where data that is included in external calls to smart contract functions gets stored.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Information in `calldata` is published on the blockchain, allowing anyone to reconstruct the rollup’s state independently.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups use compression techniques to reduce transaction data—for example, accounts are represented by an index rather than an address, which saves 28 bytes of data.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Onchain data publication is a significant cost for rollups, so data compression can reduce fees for users.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] A ZK-rollup chain is an offchain protocol that operates on top of the Ethereum blockchain and is managed by onchain Ethereum smart contracts.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups execute transactions outside of Mainnet, but periodically commit offchain transaction batches to an onchain rollup contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This transaction record is immutable, much like the Ethereum blockchain, and forms the ZK-rollup chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] **Offchain virtual machine (VM)**: While the ZK-rollup protocol lives on Ethereum, transaction execution and state storage happen on a separate virtual machine independent of the EVM.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This offchain VM is the execution environment for transactions on the ZK-rollup and serves as the secondary layer or "layer 2" for the ZK-rollup protocol.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Validity proofs verified on Ethereum Mainnet guarantee the correctness of state transitions in the offchain VM.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups are "hybrid scaling solutions"—offchain protocols that operate independently but derive security from Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Specifically, the Ethereum network enforces the validity of state updates on the ZK-rollup and guarantees the availability of data behind every update to the rollup's state.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] As a result, ZK-rollups are considerably safer than pure offchain scaling solutions, such as sidechains, which are responsible for their security properties, or validiums, which also verify transactions on Ethereum with validity proofs, but store transaction data elsewhere.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups publish state data for every transaction processed offchain to Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] With this data, it is possible for individuals or businesses to reproduce the rollup’s state and validate the chain themselves.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Ethereum makes this data available to all participants of the network as `calldata`.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups don’t need to publish much transaction data onchain because validity proofs already verify the authenticity of state transitions.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Nevertheless, storing data onchain is still important because it allows permissionless, independent verification of the L2 chain's state which in turn allows anyone to submit batches of transactions, preventing malicious operators from censoring or freezing the chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Onchain is required for users to interact with the rollup.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Without access to state data users cannot query their account balance or initiate transactions (e.g., withdrawals) that rely on state information.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Ethereum acts as a settlement layer for ZK-rollups: L2 transactions are finalized only if the L1 contract accepts the validity proof.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This eliminates the risk of malicious operators corrupting the chain (e.g., stealing rollup funds) since every transaction must be approved on Mainnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Also, Ethereum guarantees that user operations cannot be reversed once finalized on L1.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Most ZK-rollups use a "supernode" (the operator) to execute transactions, produce batches, and submit blocks to L1.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] While this ensures efficiency, it increases the risk of censorship: malicious ZK-rollup operators can censor users by refusing to include their transactions in batches.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] As a security measure, ZK-rollups allow users to submit transactions directly to the rollup contract on Mainnet if they think they are being censored by the operator.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This allows users to force an exit from the ZK-rollup to Ethereum without having to rely on the operator’s permission.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Users in the ZK-rollup sign transactions and submit to L2 operators for processing and inclusion in the next batch.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] In some cases, the operator is a centralized entity, called a sequencer, who executes transactions, aggregates them into batches, and submits to L1.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The sequencer in this system is the only entity allowed to produce L2 blocks and add rollup transactions to the ZK-rollup contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Other ZK-rollups may rotate the operator role by using a proof-of-stake validator set.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Prospective operators deposit funds in the rollup contract, with the size of each stake influencing the staker’s chances of getting selected to produce the next rollup batch.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The operator’s stake can be slashed if they act maliciously, which incentivizes them to post valid blocks.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] As explained, transaction data is published on Ethereum as `calldata`.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] `calldata` is a data area in a smart contract used to pass arguments to a function and behaves similarly to memory.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] While `calldata` isn’t stored as part of Ethereum’s state, it persists onchain as part of the Ethereum chain's history logs (opens in a new tab).
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] `calldata` does not affect Ethereum's state, making it a cheap way to store data onchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The `calldata` keyword often identifies the smart contract method being called by a transaction and holds inputs to the method in the form of an arbitrary sequence of bytes.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups use `calldata` to publish compressed transaction data onchain; the rollup operator simply adds a new batch by calling the required function in the rollup contract and passes the compressed data as function arguments.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This helps reduce costs for users since a large part of rollup fees go toward storing transaction data onchain.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The ZK-rollup’s state, which includes L2 accounts and balances, is represented as a Merkle tree.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] A cryptographic hash of the Merkle tree’s root (Merkle root) is stored in the onchain contract, allowing the rollup protocol to track changes in the state of the ZK-rollup.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The rollup transitions to a new state after the execution of a new set of transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The operator who initiated the state transition is required to compute a new state root and submit to the onchain contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] If the validity proof associated with the batch is authenticated by the verifier contract, the new Merkle root becomes the ZK-rollup’s canonical state root.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Besides computing state roots, the ZK-rollup operator also creates a batch root—the root of a Merkle tree comprising all transactions in a batch.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] When a new batch is submitted, the rollup contract stores the batch root, allowing users to prove a transaction (e.g., a withdrawal request) was included in the batch.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Users will have to provide transaction details, the batch root, and a Merkle proof showing the inclusion path.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The new state root that the ZK-rollup operator submits to the L1 contract is the result of updates to the rollup’s state.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Say Alice sends 10 tokens to Bob, the operator simply decreases Alice’s balance by 10 and increments Bob’s balance by 10.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The operator then hashes the updated account data, rebuilds the rollup's Merkle tree, and submits the new Merkle root to the onchain contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] But the rollup contract won’t automatically accept the proposed state commitment until the operator proves the new Merkle root resulted from correct updates to the rollup’s state.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The ZK-rollup operator does this by producing a validity proof, a succinct cryptographic commitment verifying the correctness of batched transactions.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Validity proofs allow parties to prove the correctness of a statement without revealing the statement itself—hence, they are also called zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups use validity proofs to confirm the correctness of offchain state transitions without having to re-execute transactions on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] These proofs can come in the form of a ZK-SNARK (opens in a new tab) (Zero-Knowledge Succinct Non-Interactive Argument of Knowledge) or ZK-STARK (opens in a new tab) (Zero-Knowledge Scalable Transparent Argument of Knowledge).
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Both SNARKs and STARKs help attest to the integrity of offchain computation in ZK-rollups, although each proof type has distinctive features.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] For the ZK-SNARK protocol to work, creating a Common Reference String (CRS) is necessary: the CRS provides public parameters for proving and verifying validity proofs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The security of the proving system depends on the CRS setup; if information used to create public parameters fall into the possession of malicious actors they may be able to generate false validity proofs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Some ZK-rollups attempt to solve this problem by using a multi-party computation ceremony (MPC) (opens in a new tab), involving trusted individuals, to generate public parameters for the ZK-SNARK circuit.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Each party contributes some randomness (called "toxic waste") to the construct the CRS, which they must destroy immediately.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Trusted setups are used because they increase the security of the CRS setup.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] As long as one honest participant destroys their input, the security of the ZK-SNARK system is guaranteed.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Still, this approach requires trusting those involved to delete their sampled randomness and not undermine the system's security guarantees.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Trust assumptions aside, ZK-SNARKs are popular for their small proof sizes and constant-time verification.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] As proof verification on L1 constitutes the larger cost of operating a ZK-rollup, L2s use ZK-SNARKs to generate proofs that can be verified quickly and cheaply on Mainnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Like ZK-SNARKs, ZK-STARKs prove the validity of offchain computation without revealing the inputs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] However, ZK-STARKs are considered an improvement on ZK-SNARKs because of their scalability and transparency.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-STARKs are 'transparent', as they can work without the trusted setup of a Common Reference String (CRS).
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Instead, ZK-STARKs rely on publicly verifiable randomness to set up parameters for generating and verifying proofs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-STARKs also provide more scalability because the time needed to prove and verify validity proofs increases *quasilinearly* in relation to the complexity of the underlying computation.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] With ZK-SNARKs, proving and verification times scale *linearly* in relation to the size of the underlying computation.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This means ZK-STARKs require less time than ZK-SNARKs for proving and verifying when large datasets are involved, making them useful for high-volume applications.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-STARKs are also secure against quantum computers, while the Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC) used in ZK-SNARKs is widely believed to be susceptible to quantum computing attacks.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The downside to ZK-STARKs is that they produce larger proof sizes, which are more expensive to verify on Ethereum.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Before accepting transactions, the operator will perform the usual checks.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Once the ZK-rollup node has enough transactions, it aggregates them into a batch and compiles inputs for the proving circuit to compile into a succinct ZK-proof.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The proving circuit computes the validity proof by "looping" over each transaction and performing the same checks the operator completed before processing the transaction.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] First, it verifies the sender's account is part of the existing state root using the provided Merkle proof.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Then it reduces the sender's balance, increases their nonce, hashes the updated account data and combines it with the Merkle proof to generate a new Merkle root.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This Merkle root reflects the sole change in the ZK-rollup's state: a change in the sender's balance and nonce.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This is possible because the Merkle proof used to prove the account's existence is used to derive the new state root.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The proving circuit performs the same process on the receiver's account.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] It checks if the receiver's account exists under the intermediate state root (using the Merkle proof), increases their balance, re-hashes the account data and combines it with the Merkle proof to generate a new state root.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The process repeats for every transaction; each "loop" creates a new state root from updating the sender's account and a subsequent new root from updating the receiver's account.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] As explained, every update to the state root represents one part of the rollup's state tree changing.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The ZK-proving circuit iterates over the entire transaction batch, verifying the sequence of updates that result in a final state root after the last transaction is executed.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The last Merkle root computed becomes the newest canonical state root of the ZK-rollup.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] After the proving circuit verifies the correctness of state updates, the L2 operator submits the computed validity proof to the verifier contract on L1.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] If the proof satisfies the circuit (i.e., it is valid), it means that there exists a sequence of valid transactions that transition the rollup from the previous state (cryptographically fingerprinted by the pre-state root) to a new state (cryptographically fingerprinted by the post-state root).
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] If the pre-state root matches the root stored in the rollup contract, and the proof is valid, the rollup contract takes the post-state root from the proof and updates its state tree to reflect the rollup's changed state.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Users enter the ZK-rollup by depositing tokens in the rollup's contract deployed on the L1 chain.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This transaction is queued up since only operators can submit transactions to the rollup contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] If the pending deposit queue starts filling up, the ZK-rollup operator will take the deposit transactions and submit them to the rollup contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Once the user's funds are in the rollup, they can start transacting by sending transactions to the operator for processing.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Users can verify balances on the rollup by hashing their account data, sending the hash to the rollup contract, and providing a Merkle proof to verify against the current state root.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Withdrawing from a ZK-rollup to L1 is straightforward.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The user initiates the exit transaction by sending their assets on the rollup to a specified account for burning.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] If the operator includes the transaction in the next batch, the user can submit a withdrawal request to the onchain contract.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The rollup contract hashes the transaction data, checks if the batch root exists, and uses the Merkle proof to check if the transaction hash is part of the batch root.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Afterward, the contract executes the exit transaction and sends funds to the user's chosen address on L1.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Unlike optimistic rollups, ZK-rollups are not readily compatible with the Ethereum Virtual Machine (EVM).
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Proving general-purpose EVM computation in circuits is more difficult and resource-intensive than proving simple computations (like the token transfer described previously).
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] However, advances in zero-knowledge technology (opens in a new tab) are igniting renewed interest in wrapping EVM computation in zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] These efforts are geared towards creating a zero-knowledge EVM (zkEVM) implementation that can efficiently verify the correctness of program execution.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] A zkEVM recreates existing EVM opcodes for proving/verification in circuits, allowing to execute smart contracts.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Like the EVM, a zkEVM transitions between states after computation is performed on some inputs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The difference is that the zkEVM also creates zero-knowledge proofs to verify the correctness of every step in the program’s execution.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Validity proofs could verify the correctness of operations that touch the VM’s state (memory, stack, storage) and the computation itself (i.e., did the operation call the right opcodes and execute them correctly?).
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The introduction of EVM-compatible ZK-rollups is expected to help developers leverage the scalability and security guarantees of zero-knowledge proofs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] More importantly, compatibility with native Ethereum infrastructure means developers can build ZK-friendly dapps using familiar (and battle-tested) tooling and languages.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] How much users pay for transactions on ZK-rollups is dependent on the gas fee, just like on Ethereum Mainnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] **Data publication**: ZK-rollups publish state data for every transaction to Ethereum as `calldata`.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] `calldata` costs are currently governed by EIP-1559 (opens in a new tab), which stipulates a cost of 16 gas for non-zero bytes and 4 gas for zero bytes of `calldata`, respectively.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The cost paid on each transaction is influenced by how much `calldata` needs to be posted onchain for it.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] **L2 operator fees**: This is the amount paid to the rollup operator as compensation for computational costs incurred in processing transactions, much like transaction "priority fees (tips)" on Ethereum Mainnet.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] **Proof generation and verification**: ZK-rollup operators must produce validity proofs for transaction batches, which is resource-intensive.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Verifying zero-knowledge proofs on Mainnet also costs gas (~ 500,000 gas).
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Apart from batching transactions, ZK-rollups reduce fees for users by compressing transaction data.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] You can see a real-time overview (opens in a new tab) of how it costs to use Ethereum ZK-rollups.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups extend the throughput on Ethereum’s base layer by taking computation offchain, but the real boost for scaling comes from compressing transaction data.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Ethereum’s block size limits the data each block can hold and, by extension, the number of transactions processed per block.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] By compressing transaction-related data, ZK-rollups significantly increase the number of transactions processed per block.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] ZK-rollups can compress transaction data better than optimistic rollups since they don't have to post all the data required to validate each transaction.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] They only have to post the minimal data required to rebuild the latest state of accounts and balances on the rollup.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] An advantage of zero-knowledge proofs is that proofs can verify other proofs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] For example, a single ZK-SNARK can verify other ZK-SNARKs.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Such "proof-of-proofs" are called recursive proofs and dramatically increase throughput on ZK-rollups.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Currently, validity proofs are generated on a block-by-block basis and submitted to the L1 contract for verification.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] However, verifying single block proofs limits the throughput that ZK-rollups can achieve since only one block can be finalized when the operator submits a proof.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] Recursive proofs, however, make it possible to finalize several blocks with one validity proof.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] This is because the proving circuit recursively aggregates multiple block proofs until one final proof is created.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The L2 operator submits this recursive proof, and if the contract accepts it, all the relevant blocks will be finalized instantly.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] With recursive proofs, the number of ZK-rollup transactions that can be finalized on Ethereum at intervals increases.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] The projects below use zkEVM technology to build Layer 2 rollups.
[src:layer2-rollups/scaling-zk-rollups] , which would enable validators to verify Ethereum blocks without re-executing transactions.
